\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 -o-}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 The library bench's cold iron bit into Eddie's thighs as he stared at the half-empty glue pot. Dried paste crusted his fingernails - flecks of white like shattered porcelain against his skin. Around him, the campus hummed with ordinary life: a study group debating spell theory, first-years giggling over shared notes, the distant chime of the clocktower. None of them knew. None of them cared.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 His thumb brushed Madeleine's remaining poster. The paper remembered her better than he did now - that precise arch of her eyebrow when explaining his failures.\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 "Your magic isn't broken,"}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~she'd said last winter, steam from her tea curling between them in the library's forbidden snacks corner.\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 "It's older than these textbooks. Older than the university's foundations."}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Her fingertip had traced the strange sigils his spells left behind.\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 "The stones remember what the professors forgot."}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 A shadow fell across the posters. Red hair catching the sun like copper wire. The scent of cinnamon and ink - Madeleine always smelled like the library's restricted section after hours. A paper cup appeared in his vision, the university caf\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u233\'E9's logo smudged where her thumb rested.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 "Oi mate, you there?"}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The cup wavered. Red darkened to dirty blond. The hand holding it bore Will's knuckle scar from last semester's bar fight. Madeleine's knowing smile fractured into Will's lopsided grin as Eddie blinked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 "Drink up." Will cracked open a beer can with his free hand, the hiss loud as spellwork in the quiet space between them. "You look like you've seen a ghost."}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Eddie took the proffered drink. The aluminum burned with cold where Will's fingers had been. "Yeah," he lied, the word sticking to his dry throat. "Thanks."}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The poster's fluttering edges sounded like whispering voices as Madeleine's face tilted skyward. Eddie's fingers dented the beer can, the cold metal biting into his palm. Condensation dripped onto his trousers like tears he couldn't shed.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 "I should've known." The words tore from somewhere raw beneath his ribs. "Months of sharing meals, of late-night study sessions..." His thumb rubbed at the can's tab, back and forth like a ward against evil. "How many times did he sit right there"\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 he jerked his chin toward the empty bench beside them\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 "laughing at how stupid we were?"}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Will's hand closed around Eddie's forearm, calluses scraping against skin. "The best liars don't wear masks." His usual boisterous tone had been stripped down to something quieter, harder. "They wear smiles."}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Eddie shook his head, unconvinced. "But I should have seen it. I was seeing him for months, for crying out loud! There were signs, little things that just didn't sit right. I ignored them. And now Madeleine..." }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 "Ed, listen to me man." He said firmly. "You can't blame yourself for this. You ain\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t mind readers. Nobody expects you to see through people, it\u8217\'92s not your fault."}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A heavy silence descended upon them, broken only by the distant sounds of students hurrying to their evening classes. Finally, after a long moment, Will spoke again, her voice softer now, laced with a hint of curiosity.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 "You cared a lot about her, didn't you, Ed?" He asked, a knowing smile playing on her lips.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Eddie met his gaze, a flicker of surprise crossing his features. He hesitated for a moment, then a small, genuine smile tugged at the corner of his mouth. "Yeah," he admitted sheepishly. "More than I ever admitted\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 I guess."}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 The last of the sunlight bled out over the library's spires, painting Will's profile in alpine gold. He turned the empty beer can between his hands, the aluminum crunching like packed snow under boots.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 "You ever hear how I ended up at Edenfield?" His Isgardian accent thickened, vowels rounding like river stones. "Back in Frostford Vale up north, there was this girl. Worked at the mead hall\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 I was still a blacksmith back then." A muscle jumped in his jaw. "Had about as much charm as a startled reindeer, so naturally I never\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 "}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The can collapsed in his grip with a sound like breaking ice.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The wind carried the distant chime of the university clock. Will's fingers absently traced the scar on his knuckles\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the one Eddie now realized might've come from something more personal than a bar fight. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 "Next summer when I went home, she was wearing another man's ring." He turned to Eddie, the usual mischief gone from his eyes.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Eddie studied his friend\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 really studied him. The way Will's shoulders braced against the memory like against a mountain wind. The faded scar across his knuckles from whatever brawl had followed that news. This wasn't just advice; it was a confession carved from permafrost.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Will nudged him with an elbow. "If she ever gets back," he said, jerking his chin toward Madeleine's fluttering poster, "You ring that girl before some other alchemy prick beats you to it, yeah?"}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Heat crawled up Eddie's neck. "Oh, shut up, Chester."}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 But Will was already grinning, the old mischief returning as he mimed holding a telephone. "Just sayin'. Your voice cracks less on calls than in person."}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 For the first time since the posters went up, Eddie laughed\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a raw, startled sound that scared a flock of starlings from the library's eaves. Will released him with a final rough tousle of his hair.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
